---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const pageTitle = "About Matthew Brunken - Runner, Fitness Enthusiast & Nebraska Native";
const pageDescription = "Learn about Matthew Brunken, a passionate runner and fitness professional based in Lincoln and Omaha, Nebraska. Discover his running journey, training philosophy, community involvement, and what drives his dedication to health and fitness.";
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <section class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>About Matthew Brunken</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Runner. Fitness Enthusiast. Nebraska Native.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="about-intro">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="about-grid">
        <div class="about-image">
          <img
            src="/images/profile.webp"
            alt="Matthew Brunken - Professional portrait in Nebraska"
            width="500"
            height="500"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="about-content">
          <h2>The Story of Matthew Brunken</h2>
          <p>Matthew Brunken is a dedicated runner, fitness enthusiast, and proud resident of Nebraska who has made it his mission to inspire others toward healthier, more active lifestyles. Based between Lincoln and Omaha, Nebraska's two largest cities, Matthew has cultivated a deep connection with the running community in the Cornhusker State, becoming a well-known figure among local runners and fitness enthusiasts.</p>
          <p>Born and raised in Nebraska, Matthew Brunken has always had an appreciation for the state's unique character and the strong sense of community that defines Midwestern life. However, his journey as a runner began later in life, emerging from a desire to improve his physical health and find new challenges as he matured. This late start to running has shaped his perspective and his approach to coaching and mentoring others who may be hesitant to begin their own running journeys.</p>
          <p>Today, Matthew Brunken is recognized not only for his personal running achievements but also for his commitment to giving back to the running community that has supported him throughout his journey. Whether through organized group runs, social media engagement, or one-on-one mentorship, Matthew consistently demonstrates his belief that running has the power to transform lives for the better.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="running-journey">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Matthew Brunken's Running Journey</h2>
      <p>Every runner has a unique story, and the story of Matthew Brunken is one of transformation, perseverance, and rediscovery. Like many adults who come to running later in life, Matthew initially struggled with the idea that he could become "a runner." The common misconception that running requires natural athletic ability or years of experience prevented him from embracing the sport for longer than necessary.</p>
      <p>The turning point for Matthew Brunken came when he realized that running isn't about being the fastest or the most talented—it's about showing up, putting in the work, and celebrating progress no matter how small. This mindset shift transformed his approach to training and enabled him to build sustainable habits that have kept him running consistently for years.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>The Early Days of Matthew Brunken's Running</summary>
        <p>Matthew's first attempts at running were humble, consisting of short jogs around his neighborhood that left him breathless and questioning whether running was really for him. Rather than giving up, he adjusted his expectations and began following a walk-run program that allowed him to gradually build endurance without overwhelming his body or spirit.</p>
        <p>Those early weeks and months of building a running foundation taught Matthew Brunken valuable lessons about patience, consistency, and the importance of respecting your body's limits. He learned to celebrate small victories—completing his first continuous mile, running his first 5K without walking, finishing a 10K that once seemed impossible. These lessons continue to inform his coaching philosophy today.</p>
        <p>As his fitness improved, Matthew began exploring the diverse running opportunities available in Nebraska. He discovered the joy of trail running in the state's beautiful parks and natural areas, the camaraderie of group runs organized by local running stores, and the inspiration that comes from participating in community race events.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Matthew Brunken's Running Achievements and Growth</summary>
        <p>While Matthew Brunken doesn't define himself by race times or podium finishes, his years of dedicated training have brought meaningful achievements and personal records that he is rightfully proud of. From half marathons to full marathons, from local 5Ks to destination races, each event has contributed to his growth as a runner and as a person.</p>
        <p>Perhaps more important than any single achievement is the running community Matthew has built around himself. By consistently showing up for group runs, volunteering at local races, and welcoming newcomers to the sport, Matthew has become a pillar of the running community in Lincoln and Omaha. His positive attitude and genuine enthusiasm for running are contagious, inspiring others to lace up their shoes and give running a try.</p>
        <p>Looking forward, Matthew Brunken continues to set new goals and pursue new challenges. Whether it's tackling a new distance, exploring unfamiliar running routes, or simply maintaining the consistent training habits that have served him well, Matthew approaches each day as an opportunity to grow and contribute to the running community he loves.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="philosophy">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Matthew Brunken's Running Philosophy</h2>
      <p>At the core of everything Matthew Brunken does as a runner and community member is a clear and thoughtful philosophy about what running means and how it should be approached. This philosophy has evolved over years of personal experience, countless conversations with fellow runners, and careful reflection on what truly matters in the sport.</p>

      <h3>The Principle of Consistency</h3>
      <p>Matthew Brunken believes that consistency is the foundation of successful running. While it's tempting to chase dramatic workouts or occasional bursts of intense training, sustainable progress comes from showing up day after day, week after week, month after month. This principle applies equally to beginners taking their first steps and experienced runners pursuing ambitious goals.</p>

      <h3>Joy Over Perfection</h3>
      <p>In a sport that naturally lends itself to comparison and self-criticism, Matthew Brunken actively promotes a philosophy of joy over perfection. Every run doesn't need to be a breakthrough performance. Every race doesn't need to end with a personal best. What matters most is that runners find genuine enjoyment in the act of putting one foot in front of the other.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Community and Connection</summary>
        <p>Running may begin as an individual activity, but Matthew Brunken has discovered—and consistently advocates for—the profound benefits of community connection in running. Whether through formal running clubs, informal group runs, or online communities, connecting with other runners provides motivation, accountability, and the shared joy that comes from pursuing goals together.</p>
        <p>Matthew's involvement in the Lincoln and Omaha running communities extends beyond simply participating in group activities. He makes a deliberate effort to welcome newcomers, encourage hesitant potential runners, and support fellow runners through the inevitable challenges and setbacks that everyone faces. This commitment to community reflects his belief that we're stronger together than we are alone.</p>
        <p>The running community in Nebraska, in particular, has impressed Matthew with its welcoming nature and genuine support for runners at all levels. From elite athletes competing at the highest levels to beginners just discovering the joy of running, Nebraska's running community embraces everyone who wants to be part of it.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Holistic Wellness</summary>
        <p>For Matthew Brunken, running is never just about physical fitness. It's a pathway to mental clarity, emotional balance, and spiritual connection with the natural world. This holistic understanding of running shapes how he approaches training, emphasizing the importance of rest, recovery, nutrition, and mental preparation alongside the physical aspects of the sport.</p>
        <p>Matthew frequently speaks about the meditative quality of running, the way a long run can provide clarity for solving problems or processing difficult emotions, and the deep satisfaction that comes from pushing through perceived limitations to discover new capabilities. These aspects of running may be less visible than the physical transformations, but they often prove more meaningful in the long run.</p>
        <p>Balancing running with other aspects of life presents ongoing challenges, but Matthew Brunken approaches this balance as an ongoing practice rather than a problem to be solved. He models a sustainable approach to running that doesn't require sacrificing career, family, or other important commitments. This balanced perspective makes his advice particularly valuable for adult runners who may be juggling multiple responsibilities.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="locations-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Matthew Brunken's Nebraska: Where Running Meets Home</h2>
      <p>Nebraska occupies a special place in Matthew Brunken's heart, and not just because it's home. The Cornhusker State offers exceptional opportunities for runners that rival much larger and more running-focused states. Through years of exploration, Matthew has developed deep knowledge of the best running routes, trails, and hidden gems that Nebraska has to offer.</p>

      <h3>Running in Lincoln, Nebraska</h3>
      <p>As Nebraska's capital city and home to the University of Nebraska, Lincoln offers a unique blend of small-city charm and genuine running culture. Matthew Brunken has established strong roots in Lincoln's running community, participating in regular group runs and building lasting friendships with fellow runners throughout the city.</p>
      <p>The running infrastructure in Lincoln continues to improve, with new trails and pathways connecting parks, neighborhoods, and points of interest throughout the city. Matthew particularly appreciates the commitment to creating accessible running opportunities for residents of all neighborhoods, ensuring that everyone can find safe and enjoyable routes near their homes.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Favorite Lincoln Running Routes</summary>
        <p>Among Matthew Brunken's favorite Lincoln running routes are the Wilderness Ridge Trail, which offers challenging terrain and beautiful views of the surrounding landscape, and the Steve Kenny Memorial Trail, a well-maintained pathway that provides miles of scenic running. He also enjoys exploring the neighborhoods of Lincoln, discovering quiet streets and charming vistas that many runners miss.</p>
        <p>The running stores in Lincoln have played an important role in Matthew's journey, providing not just equipment and advice but also community gathering spaces where runners can connect, share experiences, and find encouragement. The staff at these establishments have become friends and trusted advisors in Matthew's ongoing development as a runner.</p>
        <p>Race events in Lincoln attract runners from across the region, and Matthew actively participates in these community celebrations of running. The Lincoln Marathon and its associated events have become annual traditions that mark important milestones in his training calendar.</p>
      </details>

      <h3>Running in Omaha, Nebraska</h3>
      <p>Omaha, as Nebraska's largest city, presents different but equally compelling running opportunities. Matthew Brunken splits his time between both cities and has become equally connected to Omaha's vibrant running community. The Missouri River waterfront trails offer world-class running experiences that would be the pride of any city in America.</p>
      <p>The Omaha running community has welcomed Matthew Brunken as one of its own, and he in turn has contributed to its growth and vitality. From participating in group runs organized by the Omaha Running Club to supporting local race events, Matthew has immersed himself in everything that Omaha's running scene has to offer.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Omaha Running Highlights</summary>
        <p>The riverfront trails along the Missouri River provide Matthew's favorite running routes in Omaha, offering flat, fast surfaces perfect for recovery runs and speed work alike. The views of the river and the surrounding landscape create a sense of escape from the urban environment, despite the convenience of the city's location.</p>
        <p>Race events in Omaha, including the Omaha Marathon and numerous smaller community races, create regular opportunities for runners to test their training and celebrate their achievements. Matthew looks forward to these events as chances to reconnect with friends made through running and to welcome new runners into the community.</p>
        <p>The running store community in Omaha rivals that of much larger cities, with knowledgeable staff and comprehensive services that support runners at every level. Matthew maintains relationships with these establishments and frequently directs new runners to them for guidance on equipment, training, and community connection.</p>
      </details>

      <h3>Training Through Nebraska's Seasons</h3>
      <p>Running in Nebraska requires adaptability, and Matthew Brunken has developed strategies for maintaining consistent training throughout all four of the state's distinct seasons. Summer heat and humidity, autumn winds, winter cold, and spring storms each present unique challenges that Nebraska runners must learn to navigate.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Seasonal Training with Matthew Brunken</summary>
        <p>Summer running in Nebraska demands attention to hydration, timing, and heat management. Matthew adapts his training schedule to take advantage of cooler morning and evening hours, while remaining flexible enough to adjust when extreme heat makes outdoor running unsafe. These adaptations have become second nature through years of experience.</p>
        <p>Winter running presents different challenges, from cold temperatures that require careful layering to icy conditions that demand attention to footing and visibility. Matthew has developed a wardrobe and a set of habits that allow him to continue running throughout the winter months without significant disruption to his training.</p>
        <p>Spring and fall offer ideal running conditions in Nebraska, and Matthew takes full advantage of these seasons for higher-intensity training and longer runs. The variable weather of these transitional seasons keeps him prepared for whatever conditions might arise during goal races.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="community-involvement">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Matthew Brunken and the Running Community</h2>
      <p>Community involvement represents a core value in Matthew Brunken's approach to running. Having experienced firsthand the transformative power of a supportive running community, Matthew is committed to paying that gift forward by creating welcoming spaces for other runners, particularly those who may feel intimidated by the sport's sometimes intimidating culture.</p>
      <p>Matthew participates regularly in group runs organized by running stores, running clubs, and informal networks of friends who have come together through their shared love of running. These gatherings provide opportunities for learning, motivation, and the simple joy of running alongside others who understand the unique challenges and rewards of the sport.</p>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Mentoring New Runners</summary>
        <p>One of Matthew Brunken's most important contributions to the running community is his work mentoring new runners. Using his own late start as a source of inspiration and empathy, Matthew helps hesitant beginners take their first steps with confidence, showing them that running is accessible to people of all ages, shapes, sizes, and fitness backgrounds.</p>
        <p>Matthew's mentoring approach emphasizes progress over performance, celebration of small victories, and the development of sustainable habits that will serve new runners for years to come. He is patient with beginners' struggles and quick to acknowledge the very real difficulties of building new exercise habits.</p>
        <p>Many runners who have benefited from Matthew's mentorship have gone on to become mentors themselves, creating a ripple effect of support and encouragement throughout the Lincoln and Omaha running communities. This legacy of mentorship represents one of Matthew's proudest accomplishments as a runner.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="collapsible">
        <summary>Social Media and Online Presence</summary>
        <p>Matthew Brunken maintains an active presence across multiple social media platforms, using these channels to document his running journey, share training insights, and connect with runners from around the world. His Facebook profiles and Instagram account provide windows into the daily life of a dedicated Nebraska runner.</p>
        <p>Through social media, Matthew has built relationships with runners from diverse backgrounds and locations, creating a global community that complements his local connections. These online relationships provide ongoing inspiration and accountability, while also allowing Matthew to share the unique character of Nebraska running with a wider audience.</p>
        <p>Matthew uses his social media platforms responsibly, promoting positive messages about body image, mental health, and the importance of listening to your body. He consistently avoids the comparison traps and performance pressures that can make social media a source of anxiety rather than inspiration for runners.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="connect">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Connect with Matthew Brunken</h2>
      <p>Matthew Brunken welcomes connections from fellow runners, fitness enthusiasts, and anyone curious about the running lifestyle. Whether you're a seasoned marathoner, a beginner just starting your journey, or simply someone who appreciates the stories of personal transformation, Matthew would love to hear from you.</p>
      <p>Follow Matthew on social media to stay updated on his running adventures, training insights, and community activities. Reach out directly to ask questions, share your own running story, or explore collaboration opportunities. The running community grows stronger with each new connection, and Matthew looks forward to adding yours.</p>
      <div class="social-links">
        <a href="https://www.facebook.com/matthew.brunken" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="social-link">
          <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><path d="M18 2h-3a5 5 0 0 0-5 5v3H7v4h3v8h4v-8h3l1-4h-4V7a1 1 0 0 1 1-1h3z"/></svg>
          Facebook
        </a>
        <a href="https://www.instagram.com/brunkenmalex/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="social-link">
          <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><rect x="2" y="2" width="20" height="20" rx="5" ry="5"/><path d="M16 11.37A4 4 0 1 1 12.63 8 4 4 0 0 1 16 11.37z"/><line x1="17.5" y1="6.5" x2="17.51" y2="6.5"/></svg>
          Instagram
        </a>
        <a href="https://x.com/matthew_brunken" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="social-link">
          <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><path d="M18.244 2.25h3.308l-7.227 8.26 8.502 11.24H16.17l-5.214-6.817L4.99 21.75H1.68l7.73-8.835L1.254 2.25H8.08l4.713 6.231zm-1.161 17.52h1.833L7.084 4.126H5.117z"/></svg>
          X (Twitter)
        </a>
      </div>
      <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">Get in Touch</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .page-header {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2563eb 100%);
    color: white;
    padding: 4rem 0;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .page-header h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    opacity: 0.9;
  }

  .about-intro, .running-journey, .philosophy, .locations-section, .community-involvement {
    padding: 4rem 0;
    background: white;
  }

  .about-intro .container, .running-journey .container, .philosophy .container, .locations-section .container, .community-involvement .container {
    max-width: 1000px;
  }

  .about-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.5fr;
    gap: 4rem;
    align-items: start;
  }

  .about-image img {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 400px;
    border-radius: 1rem;
    box-shadow: 0 20px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
  }

  .about-content h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .about-content p {
    color: #4b5563;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .running-journey h2, .philosophy h2, .locations-section h2, .community-involvement h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .running-journey p, .philosophy p, .locations-section > .container > p, .locations-section h3, .community-involvement > .container > p {
    color: #4b5563;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .locations-section h3 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
    margin-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .philosophy h3 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: #1e3a5f;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .collapsible {
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    background: #f9fafb;
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
    padding: 1rem 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
  }

  .collapsible summary {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #2563eb;
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    padding-right: 1.5rem;
    position: relative;
  }

  .collapsible summary::after {
    content: "+";
    position: absolute;
    right: 0;
    font-weight: bold;
  }

  .collapsible[open] summary::after {
    content: "-";
  }

  .collapsible summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .collapsible p {
    color: #4b5563;
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-top: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .connect {
    padding: 4rem 0;
    background: #1e3a5f;
    color: white;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .connect h2 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .connect p {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0 auto 2rem;
    opacity: 0.9;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .social-links {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .social-link {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
    color: white;
    transition: background 0.2s;
  }

  .social-link:hover {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.2);
  }

  .connect .btn-primary {
    background-color: white;
    color: #1e3a5f;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .about-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      text-align: center;
    }

    .about-image {
      justify-self: center;
    }
  }
</style>
